Off. 2, 9 consuetudo . . . honestatem ab utilitate secernens . . . qua nulla pernicies maior hominum vitae potuit afferri. — opti- mis quibusque: so Arch. 26 optimus quisque gloria maxime ducitur. The love of fame is ‘the last infirmity of noble minds’. In optimis quibusque we have a very rare usage. The best writers use the plural of quisque only in the neuter, and that with a superlative adjective, not the fem. or, as here, the masc. plural.
